On Fri, Nov 20, 2015 at 10:07:12AM -0500, Nathan Medley wrote:
> ​Hi John,
> 
>      Thanks for listening. I think most importantly I want you to be aware
> of the vastness of the field. In doing so, I want you to listen for
> sympathetic singing sensations. When you hear the tenors sing, do you feel
> the phantom sensations of where there voices live in their bodies? Do you
> sympathetically feel how they are phonating? ​
> 
> There is a myriad of repertoire in the this world and it all has different
> considerations and different voices are more well suited to sing different
> things:
> 
> 1) Wagner and the late romantic operas -- Here a singer has to carry over a
> full orchestra and brass section in an opera house. This requires a HUGE
> instrument : Jonas Kaufmann does it very successfully. A little lighter and
> more flexible in their repertoire are Bryan Hymel and Jose Carreras
> 
> 2) Mozart and Rossini the early romantics and classical composers -- The
> orchestras are smaller for these operas and the voices usually lighter:
> Juan Diego Florez and Lawrence Brownlee
> 
> 3) Baroque Music -- The key lies in being declamatory with the text.
> Finding the rhetoric and being able to sing with instruments as equals vs.
> as simply accompaniment. The repertoire is oratorio, opera, and art songs:
> Paul Agnew, Zachary Wilder, Aaron Sheehan, John Mark Ainsley, and Rolando
> Villazon
> 
> 4) Art Song -- This is the training means for singers and becomes a
> foundation for recital singing. It was originally usually written for the
> high functioning amateur to purchase and then of course, great singers also
> sang it. Fritz Wunderlich, Ian Bostridge
> 
> 
> 
